# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: click-cli
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] A command-line option or simply option (also known as a flag or switch) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Many languages offer functionality for argument parsing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, the C POSIX library provides getopt(), Python offers a module called `argparse`, while C# provides a namespace `System.CommandLine`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In others, they are not bundled in the standard library, but rather must be used through third-party libraries.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In many languages, particularly C-derived languages, arguments are accessed through the parameters of the `main()` method.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, in C and C++, the `main` method has signature `int main(int argc, char* argv[]);`, where `argc` is the number of arguments plus the name of the program, and `argv` is an array of C-strings where `argv[0]` is the name of the program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In Java and C#, the `main()` method instead takes one parameter `args` of type `String[]` (an array of strings).
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Meanwhile, in some other languages, such as Rust, command-line arguments are accessed by a method `std::env::args()`, allowing a global point of access rather than having to be obtained from `main()`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C uses `argv` to process command-line arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C POSIX library also has functions called `getopt()` and `getopt_long()`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C++ accesses arguments the same way as C.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The POCO C++ Libraries offer a class `Poco::Util::OptionProcessor` for parsing command-line arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Boost provides a class `boost::program_options::command_line_parser`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Meanwhile, Google has a library called `gflags`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also a `argparse` library for C++17+ offers a similar API for argument parsing to Python `argparse`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C# provides the `System.CommandLine` namespace for advanced command-line argument parsing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The D programming language provides a module `std.getopt`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Go provides the `flag` package for argument parsing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Haskell provides the library `System.Console.GetOpt`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The Apache Commons library `org.apache.commons.cli` provides command-line argument parsing capabilities.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also the `gnu.getopt` library, ported from GNU getopt.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also `Getopt::Long` and `Getopt::Std` for argument parsing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] PHP uses `argc` as a count of arguments and `argv` as an array containing the values of the arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Python also has a module called `argparse` in the standard library for parsing command-line arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Racket uses a `current-command-line-arguments` parameter, and provides a `racket/cmdline` library for parsing these arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Rather than being part of the parameters of `main()` (like other C-style languages), in Rust the args are in `std::env::args()`, which returns a `std::env::Args` and is converted to a `Vec<String>` with `.collect()`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] A popular Rust library for command-line argument parsing is `clap`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript programs written for Node.js use the `process.argv` global variable.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Node.js programs are invoked by running the interpreter node interpreter with a given file, so the first two arguments will be `node` and the name of the JavaScript source file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] It is often useful to extract the rest of the arguments by slicing a sub-array from `process.argv`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript written for Bun use `Bun.argv` and the `util.parseArgs` function.
[src:click-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript written for Deno use `Deno.args` and the `parseArgs` function.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:click-cli/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In computing, the **exit status** (also **exit code** or **exit value**) of a terminated process is an integer number that is made available to its parent process (or caller).
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In DOS, this may be referred to as an **errorlevel**.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] When computer programs are executed, the operating system creates an abstract entity called a process in which the book-keeping for that program is maintained.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In multitasking operating systems such as Unix or Linux, new processes can be created by active processes.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The process that spawns another is called a *parent process*, while those created are *child processes*.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Child processes run concurrently with the parent process.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The technique of spawning child processes is used to delegate some work to a child process when there is no reason to stop the execution of the parent.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] When the child finishes executing, it exits by calling the *exit* system call.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] This system call facilitates passing the exit status code back to the parent, which can retrieve this value using the *wait* system call.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The parent and the child can have an understanding about the meaning of the exit statuses.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] For example, it is common programming practice for a child process to return (exit with) zero to the parent signifying success.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Apart from this return value from the child, other information like how the process exited, either normally or by a signal may also be available to the parent process.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The specific set of codes returned is unique to the program that sets it.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Typically it indicates success or failure.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The value of the code returned by the function or program may indicate a specific cause of failure.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] On many systems, the higher the value, the more severe the cause of the error.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Alternatively, each bit may indicate a different condition, with these being evaluated by the *or* operator together to give the final value; for example, fsck does this.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Sometimes, if the codes are designed with this purpose in mind, they can be used directly as a branch index upon return to the initiating program to avoid additional tests.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Shell scripts typically execute commands and capture their exit statuses.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] For the shell's purposes, a command which exits with a zero exit status has succeeded.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] A nonzero exit status indicates failure.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] This seemingly counter-intuitive scheme is used so there is one well-defined way to indicate success and a variety of ways to indicate various failure modes.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] When a command is terminated by a signal whose number is `N`, a shell sets the variable `$?` to a value greater than 128.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Most shells use 128+N, while ksh93 uses 256+N.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] If a command is not found, the shell should return a status of 127.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] If a command is found but is not executable, the return status should be 126.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Note that this is not the case for all shells.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] If a command fails because of an error during expansion or redirection, the exit status is greater than zero.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The C and C++ programming languages allow programs exiting or returning from the main function to signal success or failure by returning an integer, or returning the macros `EXIT_SUCCESS` and `EXIT_FAILURE`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] On Unix-like systems these are equal to `0` and `1` respectively.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] A C program may also use the `exit()` function specifying the integer status or exit macro as the first parameter, which halts the program.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The return value from `main` is passed to the `exit` function, which for values zero, `EXIT_SUCCESS` or `EXIT_FAILURE` may translate it to "an implementation defined form" of *successful termination* or *unsuccessful termination*.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Apart from `0` and the macros `EXIT_SUCCESS` and `EXIT_FAILURE`, the C standard does not define the meaning of return codes.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Rules for the use of return codes vary on different platforms (see the platform-specific sections).
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In C#, the `Main()` method typically does not return a type (its type is `void`, or if `async`, it is `System.Threading.Tasks.Task`).
[src:click-cli/exit-status] However, `Main()` may indicate a return type, of type `int`, which is returned to the operating system.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] If the `Main()` method is declared `async`, then it instead returns `System.Threading.Tasks.Task<int>`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In DOS terminology, an **errorlevel** is an integer exit code returned by an executable program or subroutine.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Errorlevels typically range from 0 to 255.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In DOS there are only 256 error codes available, but DR DOS 6.0 and higher support 16-bit error codes at least in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] With 4DOS and DR-DOS COMMAND.COM, exit codes (in batchjobs) can be set by EXIT *n* and (in CONFIG.SYS) through ERROR=*n*.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Exit statuses are often captured by batch programs through IF ERRORLEVEL commands.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Multiuser DOS supports a reserved environment variable %ERRORLVL% which gets automatically updated on return from applications.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] COMMAND.COM under DR-DOS 7.02 and higher supports a similar pseudo-environment variable %ERRORLVL% as well as %ERRORLEVEL%.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In CONFIG.SYS, DR DOS 6.0 and higher supports ONERROR to test the load status and return code of device drivers and the exit code of programs.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In Java, the `main()` does not indicate an exit code, so if needed, an exit code is manually specified through `java.lang.System::exit()`, which terminates the program and the JVM.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Any method may call `System.exit()`, unless a security manager does not permit it.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The argument serves as a status code; by convention, a nonzero status code indicates abnormal termination.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In OpenVMS, success is indicated by odd values and failure by even values.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The value is a 32-bit integer with sub-fields: control bits, facility number, message number and severity.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Severity values are divided between success (Success, Informational) and failure (Warning, Error, Fatal).
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In Plan 9's C, exit status is indicated by a string passed to the exits() function, and function main() is type void.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In Unix and other POSIX-compatible systems, the parent process can retrieve the exit status of a child process using the `wait()` family of system calls defined in POSIX header `<wait.h>`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Of these, the `waitid()` call retrieves the full exit status, but the older `wait()` and `waitpid()` calls retrieve only the least significant 8 bits of the exit status.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The `wait()` and `waitpid()` interfaces set a *status* value of type `int` packed as a bitfield with various types of child termination information.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] If the child terminated by exiting (as determined by the `WIFEXITED()` macro; the usual alternative being that it died from an uncaught signal), SUS specifies that the low-order 8 bits of the exit status can be retrieved from the status value using the `WEXITSTATUS()` macro.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In the `waitid()` system call (added with SUSv1), the child exit status and other information are no longer in a bitfield but in the structure of type `siginfo_t`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] POSIX-compatible systems typically use a convention of zero for success and nonzero for error.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Some conventions have developed as to the relative meanings of various error codes; for example GNU recommend that codes with the high bit set be reserved for serious errors.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] BSD-derived OS's have defined an extensive set of preferred interpretations: Meanings for 15 status codes 64 through 78 are defined in POSIX header `<sysexits.h>`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] These historically derive from sendmail and other message transfer agents, but they have since found use in many other programs.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] It has been deprecated and its use is discouraged.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The Advanced Bash-Scripting Guide has some information on the meaning of non-0 exit status codes.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] In Rust, `main()` may return any type that implements the trait `std::process::Termination`.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Internally on the Rust runtime, these will return `libc::EXIT_SUCCESS` upon successful execution and `libc::EXIT_FAILURE` upon failure.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Microsoft Windows uses 32-bit unsigned integers as exit codes, although the command interpreter treats them as signed.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] Exit codes are directly referenced, for example, by the command line interpreter CMD.exe in the `errorlevel` terminology inherited from DOS.
[src:click-cli/exit-status] The .NET Framework processes and the Windows PowerShell refer to it as the `ExitCode` property of the `Process` object.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The getopt function was written to be a standard mechanism that all programs could use to parse command-line options so that there would be a common interface on which everyone could depend.
[src:click-cli/getopt] As such, the original authors picked out of the variations support for single character options, multiple options specified together, and options with arguments (`-a arg` or `-aarg`), all controllable by an option string.
[src:click-cli/getopt] getopt dates back to at least 1980 and was first published by AT&T at the 1985 UNIFORUM conference in Dallas, Texas, with the intent for it to be available in the public domain.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Versions of it were subsequently picked up by other flavors of Unix (4.3BSD, Linux, etc.).
[src:click-cli/getopt] It is specified in the POSIX.2 standard as part of the unistd.h header file.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Derivatives of getopt have been created for many programming languages to parse command-line options.
[src:click-cli/getopt] A POSIX-standard companion function to `getopt` is `getsubopt`.
[src:click-cli/getopt] It parses a string of comma-separated sub-options.
[src:click-cli/getopt] getopt is a system dependent function, and its behavior depends on the implementation in the C library.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Some custom implementations like gnulib are available, however.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The conventional (POSIX and BSD) handling is that the options end when the first non-option argument is encountered, and that getopt would return -1 to signal that.
[src:click-cli/getopt] In the glibc extension, however, options are allowed *anywhere* for ease of use; getopt implicitly permutes the argument vector so it still leaves the non-options in the end.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Since POSIX already has the convention of returning -1 on `--` and skipping it, one can always portably use it as an end-of-options signifier.
[src:click-cli/getopt] A GNU extension, **getopt_long**, allows parsing of more readable, multicharacter options, which are introduced by two dashes instead of one.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The choice of two dashes allows multicharacter options (`--inum`) to be differentiated from single character options specified together (`-abc`).
[src:click-cli/getopt] The GNU extension also allows an alternative format for options with arguments: `--name=arg`.
[src:click-cli/getopt] This interface proved popular, and has been taken up (sans the permutation) by many BSD distributions including FreeBSD as well as Solaris.
[src:click-cli/getopt] An alternative way to support long options is seen in Solaris and Korn Shell (extending *optstring*), but it was not as popular.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Another common advanced extension of getopt is resetting the state of argument parsing; this is useful as a replacement of the options-anyware GNU extension, or as a way to "layer" a set of command-line interface with different options at different levels.
[src:click-cli/getopt] This is achieved in BSD systems using an optreset variable, and on GNU systems by setting optind to 0.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The command-line syntaxes for getopt-based programs is the POSIX-recommended Utility Argument Syntax.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Extensions on the syntax include the GNU convention and Sun's CLIP specification.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Here the `argc` and `argv` are defined exactly like they are in the C `main` function prototype; i.e., `argc` indicates the length of the `argv` array of C-strings.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The `optstring` contains a specification of what options to look for (normal alphanumerals except `W`), and what options to accept arguments (colons).
[src:click-cli/getopt] For example, `"vf::o:"` refers to three options: an argumentless `v`, an optional-argument `f`, and a mandatory-argument `o`.
[src:click-cli/getopt] GNU here implements a `W` extension for long option synonyms.
[src:click-cli/getopt] `getopt` itself returns an `int` that is either an option `char` or `-1` for end-of-options.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The idiom is to use a `while`-loop to go through options, and to use a `switch`-`case` statement to pick and act on options.
[src:click-cli/getopt] See the example section of this article.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The GNU extension `getopt_long` interface is similar, although it belongs to a different header file and takes an extra option for defining the "short" names of long options and some extra controls.
[src:click-cli/getopt] If a short name is not defined, `getopt` will put an index referring to the option structure in the `longindex` pointer instead.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Shell script programmers commonly want to provide a consistent way of providing options.
[src:click-cli/getopt] To achieve this goal, they turn to getopts and seek to port it to their own language.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The first attempt at porting was the program *getopt*, implemented by Unix System Laboratories (USL).
[src:click-cli/getopt] This version was unable to deal with quoting and shell metacharacters, as it shows no attempts at quoting.
[src:click-cli/getopt] In 1986, USL decided that being unsafe around metacharacters and whitespace was no longer acceptable, and they created the builtin getopts command for Unix SVR3 Bourne Shell instead.
[src:click-cli/getopt] The advantage of building the command into the shell is that it now has access to the shell's variables, so values could be written safely without quoting.
[src:click-cli/getopt] It uses the shell's own variables to track the position of current and argument positions, OPTIND and OPTARG, and returns the option name in a shell variable.
[src:click-cli/getopt] In 1995, `getopts` was included in the Single UNIX Specification version 1 / X/Open Portability Guidelines Issue 4.
[src:click-cli/getopt] Now a part of the POSIX Shell standard, getopts have spread far and wide in many other shells trying to be POSIX-compliant.
[src:click-cli/options] Adding options to commands can be accomplished with the `option()` decorator.
[src:click-cli/options] At runtime the decorator invokes the `Option` class.
[src:click-cli/options] Options in Click are distinct from positional arguments.
[src:click-cli/options] The `option()` decorator is usually passed two positional arguments: the option name and the decorated function argument name.
[src:click-cli/options] However, if the decorated function argument name is not passed in, then Click will try to infer it.
[src:click-cli/options] A simple way to name the option so that Click will infer it correctly is by taking the function argument, adding two dashes to the front and converting underscores to dashes.
[src:click-cli/options] If multiple positional arguments are prefixed with `--`, the first one declared is chosen.
[src:click-cli/options] Otherwise, the first positional argument prefixed with `-` is chosen.
[src:click-cli/options] To get the argument name, the chosen positional argument is converted to lower case, a leading `-` or `--` is removed if found, and any remaining `-` characters are replaced with `_`.
[src:click-cli/options] A simple `click.Option` takes one option name.
[src:click-cli/options] By default, it’s assumed that the decorated function argument is not required and the expected type is `str`.
[src:click-cli/options] If the decorated function takes a positional argument but the option is not passed with the command, then `None` is passed.
[src:click-cli/options] Instead of setting the `type`, you may set a default and Click will try to infer the type.
[src:click-cli/options] To make an option take multiple values, pass in `nargs`.
[src:click-cli/options] Note you may pass in any positive integer, but not -1.
[src:click-cli/options] The values are passed to the decorated function as a tuple.
[src:click-cli/options] By setting `nargs` to a specific number, each item in the resulting tuple is of the same type.
[src:click-cli/options] Alternatively, you might want to use different types for different indexes in the tuple.
[src:click-cli/options] By using a tuple literal as the `type`, `nargs` gets automatically set to the length of the tuple and the `click.Tuple` type is automatically used.
[src:click-cli/options] The multiple options format allows options to take an arbitrary number of arguments (which is called variadic).
[src:click-cli/options] The arguments are passed to the decorated function as a tuple.
[src:click-cli/options] If set, `default` must be a list or tuple.
[src:click-cli/options] Setting a string as `default` will be interpreted as a list of characters.
[src:click-cli/options] Short options made of a single character can be combined into one argument: `-abc` is equivalent to `-a -b -c`.
[src:click-cli/options] This is the standard POSIX behavior for short option stacking, and it is the reason a repeated flag like `-vvv` works with the Counting feature.
[src:click-cli/options] Multi-character short option names are not supported.
[src:click-cli/options] An argument like `-dbg` is interpreted as the combination of `-d`, `-b`, and `-g`, so Click reports `No such option: -d` if `-d` is not declared.
[src:click-cli/options] For longer option names, use a long option with the `--` prefix (like `--debug`).
[src:click-cli/options] To count the occurrence of an option, set `count=True`.
[src:click-cli/options] If the option is not passed on the command line, then the count is 0.
[src:click-cli/options] Counting is commonly used for verbosity.
[src:click-cli/options] Boolean options (boolean flags) take the values `True` or `False`.
[src:click-cli/options] The simplest case sets the default value to `False` if the flag is not passed, and `True` if it is.
[src:click-cli/options] To implement this more explicitly, declare `--{on-option}/--{off-option}`.
[src:click-cli/options] Click will automatically set `is_flag=True`.
[src:click-cli/options] If a forward slash (`/`) is contained in your option name already, you can split the parameters using `;`.
[src:click-cli/options] In Windows `/` is commonly used as the prefix character.
[src:click-cli/options] If you want to define an alias for the second option only, then you will need to use leading whitespace to disambiguate the format string.
[src:click-cli/options] To have a flag pass a value to the decorated function set `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] To mark the flag as default, set `default=True`.
[src:click-cli/options] The `default` value is given to the underlying function as-is.
[src:click-cli/options] So if you set `default=None`, the function receives `None`.
[src:click-cli/options] But there is a special case for **non-boolean** flags: if a flag has a non-boolean `flag_value` (like a string or a class), then `default=True` is interpreted as *the flag should be activated by default*.
[src:click-cli/options] The function receives the `flag_value`, not the Python `True`.
[src:click-cli/options] Because the two are equivalent, it is recommended to always use the second form and set `default` to the actual value you want.
[src:click-cli/options] This makes code more explicit and predictable.
[src:click-cli/options] This special case does **not** apply to boolean flags (where `flag_value` is `True` or `False`).
[src:click-cli/options] For boolean flags, `default=True` is the literal Python value `True`.
[src:click-cli/options] The tables below show the value received by the function for each combination of `default`, `flag_value`, and whether the flag was passed on the command line.
[src:click-cli/options] These are flags where `flag_value` is `True` or `False`.
[src:click-cli/options] The `default` value is always passed through literally without any special substitution.
[src:click-cli/options] These use secondary option names to provide both an on and off switch.
[src:click-cli/options] For these flags, `default=True` is a **special case**: it means “activate this flag by default” and resolves to the `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] All other `default` values are passed through literally.
[src:click-cli/options] ¹: `default=True` is substituted with `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] Several `flag_value` options can target the same parameter name to form a feature switch group.
[src:click-cli/options] The user picks one flag on the command line, and the function receives the corresponding `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] When the user picks none, Click falls back to whichever option claims the slot under the arbitration rules described below.
[src:click-cli/options] For non-boolean `flag_value` (strings, enum members, classes, …), place `default=True` on the option that should win when no flag is passed.
[src:click-cli/options] The substitution rule above resolves it to that option’s `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] Any other explicit `default` is passed through literally.
[src:click-cli/options] The third row is the three-state pattern: the function receives `None` when no flag is passed, distinguishable from either explicit choice.
[src:click-cli/options] When `flag_value` is `True` or `False`, the substitution rule does not apply: `default=True` is the literal Python `True`.
[src:click-cli/options] For most enable/disable cases, the pair form `--with-xyz/--without-xyz` is shorter and equivalent.
[src:click-cli/options] The multi-flag group form is useful when the on and off flags need distinct names without a shared stem, or when each flag needs its own help text.
[src:click-cli/options] When several options in a group resolve their values simultaneously, only one wins the parameter slot.
[src:click-cli/options] The full arbitration policy (source precedence, explicit-beats-auto tie-break, last-declared fallback) is enumerated under Option value resolution.
[src:click-cli/options] This section enumerates the rules Click applies when computing the value delivered to the decorated function for every option.
[src:click-cli/options] Rules are listed in the order they fire during the parsing pipeline.
[src:click-cli/options] If `flag_value` is an `int`, `float`, or `str`, the type is the matching basic type.
[src:click-cli/options] If `flag_value` is any other Python object (a class, an enum member, a `frozenset`, …), the type is `UNPROCESSED` so the value passes through unchanged.
[src:click-cli/options] Otherwise, the type is inferred from `default` if set, falling back to `StringParamType` when neither hint is available.
[src:click-cli/options] For a bare boolean flag (no `flag_value`, or `flag_value` of `True` or `False`), an unset `default` auto-derives to `False`.
[src:click-cli/options] For a non-boolean flag with a `flag_value`, `default=True` is substituted with `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] This is the “activate this flag by default” shorthand.
[src:click-cli/options] Any non-`True` `default` is passed through literally.
[src:click-cli/options] For a boolean flag with `flag_value` set, `default=True` is the literal Python `True`.
[src:click-cli/options] The substitution from rule 3 does not apply.
[src:click-cli/options] `default=None` is always a real explicit value, distinct from `UNSET` absence.
[src:click-cli/options] Any other `default` is delivered to the function unchanged after conversion through the parameter’s type.
[src:click-cli/options] **parameter default** (`ParameterSource.DEFAULT`).
[src:click-cli/options] The first source that produces a value wins.
[src:click-cli/options] Environment variables and `default_map` entries set to `Sentinel.UNSET` are skipped, so they fall through to the next source rather than supplying `UNSET` to the function.
[src:click-cli/options] If after the four sources above no explicit value was found (or only a `default_map`/`default` value was) and the option declares `prompt=`, Click prompts the user for one.
[src:click-cli/options] The resulting value is recorded as `ParameterSource.PROMPT`, which ranks above every source listed above for arbitration purposes (see Slot arbitration).
[src:click-cli/options] Several options can target the same `name` to form a feature switch group.
[src:click-cli/options] When they do, only one option’s value reaches the function.
[src:click-cli/options] **Within the default tier, explicit beats auto-derived.** An option that received an explicit `default=` keyword wins over one whose default came from `default` interpretation.
[src:click-cli/options] **Otherwise, last declared wins.** When all options in the group resolved from the same source and tier (all auto-derived defaults, or all explicit defaults), the option declared last in the source code keeps the slot.
[src:click-cli/options] To pass in a value from a specific environment variable use `envvar`.
[src:click-cli/options] If a list is passed to `envvar`, the first environment variable found is picked.
[src:click-cli/options] For flag options, there are two concepts to consider: the activation of the flag driven by the environment variable, and the value of the flag if it is activated.
[src:click-cli/options] The values read from environment variables are always strings and will require extra processing.
[src:click-cli/options] We need to transform these strings into boolean values that will determine if the flag is activated or not.
[src:click-cli/options] For boolean flags with a pair of values, the only recognized environment variable is the one provided to the `envvar` argument.
[src:click-cli/options] So an option defined as `--flag/--no-flag`, with an `envvar="FLAG"` parameter, there is no magical `NO_FLAG=<anything>` variable that is recognized.
[src:click-cli/options] Only the `FLAG=<anything>` environment variable is recognized.
[src:click-cli/options] If the flag is activated, its value is set to `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] Otherwise, the value defaults to `None`.
[src:click-cli/options] As options can accept multiple values, pulling in such values from environment variables (which are strings) is a bit more complex.
[src:click-cli/options] Click handles this by deferring customization of the behavior to the `type`.
[src:click-cli/options] For both `multiple` and `nargs` with values other than `1`, Click will invoke the `ParamType.split_envvar_value()` method to perform the splitting.
[src:click-cli/options] The default implementation for all types is to split on whitespace.
[src:click-cli/options] The exceptions to this rule are the `File` and `Path` types which both split according to the operating system’s path splitting rules.
[src:click-cli/options] On Unix systems like Linux and OS X, the splitting happens on every colon (`:`), and for Windows, splitting on every semicolon (`;`).
[src:click-cli/options] Click can deal with prefix characters besides `-` for options, including `/` and `+`, as well as others.
[src:click-cli/options] Note that alternative prefix characters are generally used very sparingly if at all within POSIX.
[src:click-cli/options] There are special considerations for using `/` as prefix character.
[src:click-cli/options] Providing the value to an option can be made optional, in which case providing only the option’s flag without a value will either show a prompt or use its `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/options] Setting `is_flag=False, flag_value=value` tells Click that the option can still be passed a value, but if only the flag is given, the value will be `flag_value`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Installing into a virtual environment is highly recommended.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Some standalone examples of Click applications are packaged with Click.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] They are available in the examples folder of the repo.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Click is based on declaring commands through decorators.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Internally, there is a non-decorator interface for advanced use cases, but it’s discouraged for high-level usage.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] A function becomes a Click command line tool by decorating it through `command()`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Why does this example use `echo()` instead of the regular `print()` function?
[src:click-cli/quickstart] The answer to this question is that Click attempts to support different environments consistently and to be very robust even when the environment is misconfigured.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Click wants to be functional at least on a basic level even if everything is completely broken.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] What this means is that the `echo()` function applies some error correction in case the terminal is misconfigured instead of dying with a `UnicodeError`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] The echo function also supports color and other styles in output.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] It will automatically remove styles if the output stream is a file.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] On Windows, colorama is automatically installed and used.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] If you don’t need this, you can also use the `print()` construct / function.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Commands can be attached to other commands of type `Group`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] This allows arbitrary nesting of scripts.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] As you can see, the `group()` decorator works like the `command()` decorator, but creates a `Group` object instead which can be given multiple subcommands that can be attached with `Group.add_command()`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] For simple scripts, it’s also possible to automatically attach and create a command by using the `Group.command()` decorator instead.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Instead of using the `@group.command()` decorator, commands can be decorated with the plain `@command()` decorator and registered with a group later with `group.add_command()`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] This could be used to split commands into multiple Python modules.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] In the code you wrote so far there is a block at the end of the file which looks like this: `if __name__ == '__main__':`.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] This is traditionally how a standalone Python file looks like.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] With Click you can continue doing that, but a better way is to package your app with an entry point.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] The first one is that installers automatically generate executable wrappers for Windows so your command line utilities work on Windows too.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] The second reason is that entry point scripts work with virtualenv on Unix without the virtualenv having to be activated.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] This is a very useful concept which allows you to bundle your scripts with all requirements into a virtualenv.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Click is perfectly equipped to work with that and in fact the rest of the documentation will assume that you are writing applications as distributed packages.
[src:click-cli/quickstart] Look at the Packaging Entry Points chapter before reading the rest as the examples assume that you will be using entry points.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:click-cli/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:click-cli/usability] The object of use can be a software application, website, book, tool, machine, process, vehicle, or anything a human interacts with.
[src:click-cli/usability] A usability study may be conducted as a primary job function by a *usability analyst* or as a secondary job function by designers, technical writers, marketing personnel, and others.
[src:click-cli/usability] It is widely used in consumer electronics, communication, and knowledge transfer objects (such as a cookbook, a document or online help) and mechanical objects such as a door handle or a hammer.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability includes methods of measuring usability, such as needs analysis and the study of the principles behind an object's perceived efficiency or elegance.
[src:click-cli/usability] In human-computer interaction and computer science, usability studies the elegance and clarity with which the interaction with a computer program or a web site (web usability) is designed.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability considers user satisfaction and utility as quality components, and aims to improve user experience through iterative design.
[src:click-cli/usability] Complex computer systems find their way into everyday life, and at the same time the market is saturated with competing brands.
[src:click-cli/usability] This has made usability more popular and widely recognized in recent years, as companies see the benefits of researching and developing their products with user-oriented methods instead of technology-oriented methods.
[src:click-cli/usability] By understanding and researching the interaction between product and user, the *usability expert* can also provide insight that is unattainable by traditional company-oriented market research.
[src:click-cli/usability] For example, after observing and interviewing users, the usability expert may identify needed functionality or design flaws that were not anticipated.
[src:click-cli/usability] A method called *contextual inquiry* does this in the naturally occurring context of the users own environment.
[src:click-cli/usability] In the user-centered design paradigm, the product is designed with its intended users in mind at all times.
[src:click-cli/usability] In the user-driven or participatory design paradigm, some of the users become actual or de facto members of the design team.
[src:click-cli/usability] The term *user friendly* is often used as a synonym for *usable*, though it may also refer to accessibility.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability describes the quality of user experience across websites, software, products, and environments.
[src:click-cli/usability] There is no consensus about the relation of the terms ergonomics (or human factors) and usability.
[src:click-cli/usability] Some think of usability as the software specialization of the larger topic of ergonomics.
[src:click-cli/usability] Others view these topics as tangential, with ergonomics focusing on physiological matters (e.g., turning a door handle) and usability focusing on psychological matters (e.g., recognizing that a door can be opened by turning its handle).
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability is also important in website development (web usability).
[src:click-cli/usability] According to Jakob Nielsen, "Studies of user behavior on the Web find a low tolerance for difficult designs or slow sites.
[src:click-cli/usability] And they don't want to learn how to use a home page.
[src:click-cli/usability] There's no such thing as a training class or a manual for a Web site.
[src:click-cli/usability] People have to be able to grasp the functioning of the site immediately after scanning the home page—for a few seconds at most." Otherwise, most casual users simply leave the site and browse or shop elsewhere.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability can also include the concept of prototypicality, which is how much a particular thing conforms to the expected shared norm, for instance, in website design, users prefer sites that conform to recognised design norms.
[src:click-cli/usability] ISO defines usability as "The extent to which a product can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction in a specified context of use." The word "usability" also refers to methods for improving ease-of-use during the design process.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability is often associated with the functionalities of the product (cf.
[src:click-cli/usability] ISO definition, below), in addition to being solely a characteristic of the user interface (cf. framework of system acceptability, also below, which separates *usefulness* into *usability* and *utility*).
[src:click-cli/usability] For example, in the context of mainstream consumer products, an automobile lacking a reverse gear could be considered *unusable* according to the former view, and *lacking in utility* according to the latter view.
[src:click-cli/usability] When evaluating user interfaces for usability, the definition can be as simple as "the perception of a target user of the effectiveness (fit for purpose) and efficiency (work or time required to use) of the Interface".
[src:click-cli/usability] Each component may be measured subjectively against criteria, e.g., Principles of User Interface Design, to provide a metric, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:click-cli/usability] It is important to distinguish between usability testing and usability engineering.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability testing is the measurement of ease of use of a product or piece of software.
[src:click-cli/usability] In contrast, usability engineering (UE) is the research and design process that ensures a product with good usability.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability is a non-functional requirement.
[src:click-cli/usability] As with other non-functional requirements, usability cannot be directly measured but must be quantified by means of indirect measures or attributes such as, for example, the number of reported problems with ease-of-use of a system.
[src:click-cli/usability] The term intuitive is often listed as a desirable trait in usable interfaces, sometimes used as a synonym for learnable.
[src:click-cli/usability] In the past, Jef Raskin discouraged using this term in user interface design, claiming that easy to use interfaces are often easy because of the user's exposure to previous similar systems, thus the term 'familiar' should be preferred.
[src:click-cli/usability] As an example: Two vertical lines "||" on media player buttons do not intuitively mean "pause"—they do so by convention.
[src:click-cli/usability] Researchers have also investigated intuitive interaction for older people, people living with dementia, and children.
[src:click-cli/usability] Some have argued that aiming for "intuitive" interfaces (based on reusing existing skills with interaction systems) could lead designers to discard a better design solution only because it would require a novel approach and to stick with boring designs.
[src:click-cli/usability] However, applying familiar features into a new interface has been shown not to result in boring design if designers use creative approaches rather than simple copying.
[src:click-cli/usability] The throwaway remark that "the only intuitive interface is the nipple; everything else is learned." is still occasionally mentioned.
[src:click-cli/usability] Any breastfeeding mother or lactation consultant will tell you this is inaccurate and the nipple does in fact require learning on both sides.
[src:click-cli/usability] However, the term intuitive interaction has become well accepted in the research community over the past 20 or so years and, although not perfect, it should probably be accepted and used.
[src:click-cli/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 ("Ergonomics of human-system interaction—Usability methods supporting human-centered design") is an International Standards Organization (ISO) standard that provides information on human-centered usability methods that can be used for design and evaluation.
[src:click-cli/usability] It details the advantages, disadvantages, and other factors relevant to using each usability method.
[src:click-cli/usability] It explains the implications of the stage of the life cycle and the individual project characteristics for the selection of usability methods and provides examples of usability methods in context.
[src:click-cli/usability] The main users of ISO/TR 16982:2002 are project managers.
[src:click-cli/usability] It therefore addresses technical human factors and ergonomics issues only to the extent necessary to allow managers to understand their relevance and importance in the design process as a whole.
[src:click-cli/usability] The guidance in ISO/TR 16982:2002 can be tailored for specific design situations by using the lists of issues characterizing the context of use of the product to be delivered.
[src:click-cli/usability] Selection of appropriate usability methods should also take account of the relevant life-cycle process.
[src:click-cli/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 is restricted to methods that are widely used by usability specialists and project managers.
[src:click-cli/usability] It does *not* specify the details of how to implement or carry out the usability methods described.
[src:click-cli/usability] ISO 9241 is a multi-part standard that covers a number of aspects of people working with computers.
[src:click-cli/usability] Although originally titled *Ergonomic requirements for office work with visual display terminals (VDTs)*, it has been retitled to the more generic *Ergonomics of Human System Interaction*.
[src:click-cli/usability] As part of this change, ISO is renumbering some parts of the standard so that it can cover more topics, e.g. tactile and haptic interaction.
[src:click-cli/usability] The first part to be renumbered was part 10 in 2006, now part 110.
[src:click-cli/usability] IEC 62366-1:2015 + COR1:2016 & IEC/TR 62366-2 provide guidance on usability engineering specific to a medical device.
[src:click-cli/usability] Any system or device designed for use by people should be easy to use, easy to learn, easy to remember (the instructions), and helpful to users.
[src:click-cli/usability] The design team should be user-driven and it should be in direct contact with potential users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Several evaluation methods, including personas, cognitive modeling, inspection, inquiry, prototyping, and testing methods may contribute to understanding potential users and their perceptions of how well the product or process works.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability considerations, such as who the users are and their experience with similar systems must be examined.
[src:click-cli/usability] As part of understanding users, this knowledge must "...be played against the tasks that the users will be expected to perform." This includes the analysis of what tasks the users will perform, which are most important, and what decisions the users will make while using your system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Designers must understand how cognitive and emotional characteristics of users will relate to a proposed system.
[src:click-cli/usability] One way to stress the importance of these issues in the designers' minds is to use personas, which are made-up representative users.
[src:click-cli/usability] See below for further discussion of personas.
[src:click-cli/usability] Another more expensive but more insightful method is to have a panel of potential users work closely with the design team from the early stages.
[src:click-cli/usability] Test the system early on, and test the system on real users using behavioral measurements.
[src:click-cli/usability] This includes testing the system for both learnability and usability.
[src:click-cli/usability] It is important in this stage to use quantitative usability specifications such as time and errors to complete tasks and number of users to test, as well as examine performance and attitudes of the users testing the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Finally, "reviewing or demonstrating" a system before the user tests it can result in misleading results.
[src:click-cli/usability] The emphasis of empirical measurement is on measurement, both informal and formal, which can be carried out through a variety of evaluation methods.
[src:click-cli/usability] Iterative design is a design methodology based on a cyclic process of prototyping, testing, analyzing, and refining a product or process.
[src:click-cli/usability] Based on the results of testing the most recent iteration of a design, changes and refinements are made.
[src:click-cli/usability] This process is intended to ultimately improve the quality and functionality of a design.
[src:click-cli/usability] In iterative design, interaction with the designed system is used as a form of research for informing and evolving a project, as successive versions, or iterations of a design are implemented.
[src:click-cli/usability] The key requirements for Iterative Design are: identification of required changes, an ability to make changes, and a willingness to make changes.
[src:click-cli/usability] When a problem is encountered, there is no set method to determine the correct solution.
[src:click-cli/usability] Rather, there are empirical methods that can be used during system development or after the system is delivered, usually a more inopportune time.
[src:click-cli/usability] Ultimately, iterative design works towards meeting goals such as making the system user friendly, easy to use, easy to operate, simple, etc.
[src:click-cli/usability] There are a variety of usability evaluation methods.
[src:click-cli/usability] Certain methods use data from users, while others rely on usability experts.
[src:click-cli/usability] There are usability evaluation methods for all stages of design and development, from product definition to final design modifications.
[src:click-cli/usability] When choosing a method, consider cost, time constraints, and appropriateness.
[src:click-cli/usability] For a brief overview of methods, see Comparison of usability evaluation methods or continue reading below.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability methods can be further classified into the subcategories below.
[src:click-cli/usability] Cognitive modeling involves creating a computational model to estimate how long it takes people to perform a given task.
[src:click-cli/usability] Models are based on psychological principles and experimental studies to determine times for cognitive processing and motor movements.
[src:click-cli/usability] Cognitive models can be used to improve user interfaces or predict problem errors and pitfalls during the design process.
[src:click-cli/usability] With parallel design, several people create an initial design from the same set of requirements.
[src:click-cli/usability] Each person works independently, and when finished, shares concepts with the group.
[src:click-cli/usability] The design team considers each solution, and each designer uses the best ideas to further improve their own solution.
[src:click-cli/usability] This process helps generate many different, diverse ideas, and ensures that the best ideas from each design are integrated into the final concept.
[src:click-cli/usability] This process can be repeated several times until the team is satisfied with the final concept.
[src:click-cli/usability] Sometimes it is useful to break a task down and analyze each individual aspect separately.
[src:click-cli/usability] This helps the tester locate specific areas for improvement.
[src:click-cli/usability] To do this, it is necessary to understand how the human brain processes information.
[src:click-cli/usability] A model of the human processor is shown below.
[src:click-cli/usability] Many studies have been done to estimate the cycle times, decay times, and capacities of each of these processors.
[src:click-cli/usability] Variables that affect these can include subject age, aptitudes, ability, and the surrounding environment.
[src:click-cli/usability] Long-term memory is believed to have an infinite capacity and decay time.
[src:click-cli/usability] Keystroke level modeling is essentially a less comprehensive version of GOMS that makes simplifying assumptions in order to reduce calculation time and complexity.
[src:click-cli/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve observation of users by an experimenter, or the testing and evaluation of a program by an expert reviewer.
[src:click-cli/usability] They provide more quantitative data as tasks can be timed and recorded.
[src:click-cli/usability] Card sorting is a way to involve users in grouping information for a website's usability review.
[src:click-cli/usability] Participants in a card sorting session are asked to organize the content from a Web site in a way that makes sense to them.
[src:click-cli/usability] Participants review items from a Web site and then group these items into categories.
[src:click-cli/usability] Card sorting helps to learn how users think about the content and how they would organize the information on the Web site.
[src:click-cli/usability] Card sorting helps to build the structure for a Web site, decide what to put on the home page, and label the home page categories.
[src:click-cli/usability] It also helps to ensure that information is organized on the site in a way that is logical to users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Tree testing is a way to evaluate the effectiveness of a website's top-down organization.
[src:click-cli/usability] Participants are given "find it" tasks, then asked to drill down through successive text lists of topics and subtopics to find a suitable answer.
[src:click-cli/usability] Tree testing evaluates the findability and labeling of topics in a site, separate from its navigation controls or visual design.
[src:click-cli/usability] Ethnographic analysis is derived from anthropology.
[src:click-cli/usability] Field observations are taken at a site of a possible user, which track the artifacts of work such as Post-It notes, items on desktop, shortcuts, and items in trash bins.
[src:click-cli/usability] These observations also gather the sequence of work and interruptions that determine the user's typical day.
[src:click-cli/usability] Heuristic evaluation is a usability engineering method for finding and assessing usability problems in a user interface design as part of an iterative design process.
[src:click-cli/usability] It involves having a small set of evaluators examining the interface and using recognized usability principles (the "heuristics").
[src:click-cli/usability] It is the most popular of the usability inspection methods, as it is quick, cheap, and easy.
[src:click-cli/usability] Heuristic evaluation was developed to aid in the design of computer user-interface design.
[src:click-cli/usability] It relies on expert reviewers to discover usability problems and then categorize and rate them by a set of principles (heuristics.) It is widely used based on its speed and cost-effectiveness.
[src:click-cli/usability] Jakob Nielsen's list of ten heuristics is the most commonly used in industry.
[src:click-cli/usability] These are ten general principles for user interface design.
[src:click-cli/usability] They are called "heuristics" because they are more in the nature of rules of thumb than specific usability guidelines.
[src:click-cli/usability] Thus, by determining which guidelines are violated, the usability of a device can be determined.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability inspection is a review of a system based on a set of guidelines.
[src:click-cli/usability] The review is conducted by a group of experts who are deeply familiar with the concepts of usability in design.
[src:click-cli/usability] The experts focus on a list of areas in design that have been shown to be troublesome for users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Pluralistic Inspections are meetings where users, developers, and human factors people meet together to discuss and evaluate step by step of a task scenario.
[src:click-cli/usability] As more people inspect the scenario for problems, the higher the probability to find problems.
[src:click-cli/usability] In addition, the more interaction in the team, the faster the usability issues are resolved.
[src:click-cli/usability] In consistency inspection, expert designers review products or projects to ensure consistency across multiple products to look if it does things in the same way as their own designs.
[src:click-cli/usability] Activity analysis is a usability method used in preliminary stages of development to get a sense of situation.
[src:click-cli/usability] It involves an investigator observing users as they work in the field.
[src:click-cli/usability] Also referred to as user observation, it is useful for specifying user requirements and studying currently used tasks and subtasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] The data collected are qualitative and useful for defining the problem.
[src:click-cli/usability] The following usability evaluation methods involve collecting qualitative data from users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Although the data collected is subjective, it provides valuable information on what the user wants.
[src:click-cli/usability] Task analysis means learning about users' goals and users' ways of working.
[src:click-cli/usability] Task analysis can also mean figuring out what more specific tasks users must do to meet those goals and what steps they must take to accomplish those tasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] Along with user and task analysis, a third analysis is often used: understanding users' environments (physical, social, cultural, and technological environments).
[src:click-cli/usability] A focus group is a focused discussion where a moderator leads a group of participants through a set of questions on a particular topic.
[src:click-cli/usability] Although typically used as a marketing tool, focus groups are sometimes used to evaluate usability.
[src:click-cli/usability] Used in the product definition stage, a group of 6 to 10 users are gathered to discuss what they desire in a product.
[src:click-cli/usability] An experienced focus group facilitator is hired to guide the discussion to areas of interest for the developers.
[src:click-cli/usability] Focus groups are typically videotaped to help get verbatim quotes, and clips are often used to summarize opinions.
[src:click-cli/usability] The data gathered is not usually quantitative, but can help get an idea of a target group's opinion.
[src:click-cli/usability] Surveys have the advantages of being inexpensive, require no testing equipment, and results reflect the users' opinions.
[src:click-cli/usability] When written carefully and given to actual users who have experience with the product and knowledge of design, surveys provide useful feedback on the strong and weak areas of the usability of a design.
[src:click-cli/usability] This is a very common method and often does not appear to be a survey, but just a warranty card.
[src:click-cli/usability] It is often very difficult for designers to conduct usability tests with the exact system being designed.
[src:click-cli/usability] Cost constraints, size, and design constraints usually lead the designer to creating a prototype of the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Instead of creating the complete final system, the designer may test different sections of the system, thus making several small models of each component of the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Prototyping is an attitude and an output, as it is a process for generating and reflecting on tangible ideas by allowing failure to occur early. prototyping helps people to see what could be of communicating a shared vision, and of giving shape to the future.
[src:click-cli/usability] The types of usability prototypes may vary from using paper models, index cards, hand drawn models, or storyboards.
[src:click-cli/usability] This tool kit is a wide library of methods that used the traditional programming language and it is primarily developed for computer programmers.
[src:click-cli/usability] The code created for testing in the tool kit approach can be used in the final product.
[src:click-cli/usability] However, to get the highest benefit from the tool, the user must be an expert programmer.
[src:click-cli/usability] The two elements of this approach include a parts library and a method used for identifying the connection between the parts.
[src:click-cli/usability] This approach can be used by almost anyone and it is a great asset for designers with repetitive tasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] This approach is a combination of the tool kit approach and the part kit approach.
[src:click-cli/usability] Both the dialogue designers and the programmers are able to interact with this prototyping tool.
[src:click-cli/usability] Rapid prototyping is a method used in early stages of development to validate and refine the usability of a system.
[src:click-cli/usability] It can be used to quickly and cheaply evaluate user-interface designs without the need for an expensive working model.
[src:click-cli/usability] This can help remove hesitation to change the design, since it is implemented before any real programming begins.
[src:click-cli/usability] One such method of rapid prototyping is paper prototyping.
[src:click-cli/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve testing of subjects for the most quantitative data.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usually recorded on video, they provide task completion time and allow for observation of attitude.
[src:click-cli/usability] Regardless to how carefully a system is designed, all theories must be tested using usability tests.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability tests involve typical users using the system (or product) in a realistic environment [see simulation].
[src:click-cli/usability] Observation of the user's behavior, emotions, and difficulties while performing different tasks, often identify areas of improvement for the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] While conducting usability tests, designers must use usability metrics to identify what it is they are going to measure, or the usability metrics.
[src:click-cli/usability] These metrics are often variable, and change in conjunction with the scope and goals of the project.
[src:click-cli/usability] The number of subjects being tested can also affect usability metrics, as it is often easier to focus on specific demographics.
[src:click-cli/usability] Qualitative design phases, such as general usability (can the task be accomplished?), and user satisfaction are also typically done with smaller groups of subjects.
[src:click-cli/usability] Using inexpensive prototypes on small user groups provides more detailed information, because of the more interactive atmosphere, and the designer's ability to focus more on the individual user.
[src:click-cli/usability] As the designs become more complex, the testing must become more formalized.
[src:click-cli/usability] Testing equipment will become more sophisticated and testing metrics become more quantitative.
[src:click-cli/usability] With a more refined prototype, designers often test effectiveness, efficiency, and subjective satisfaction, by asking the user to complete various tasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] These categories are measured by the percent that complete the task, how long it takes to complete the tasks, ratios of success to failure to complete the task, time spent on errors, the number of errors, rating scale of satisfactions, number of times user seems frustrated, etc.
[src:click-cli/usability] Additional observations of the users give designers insight on navigation difficulties, controls, conceptual models, etc.
[src:click-cli/usability] The ultimate goal of analyzing these metrics is to find/create a prototype design that users like and use to successfully perform given tasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] After conducting usability tests, it is important for a designer to record what was observed, in addition to why such behavior occurred and modify the model according to the results.
[src:click-cli/usability] Often it is quite difficult to distinguish the source of the design errors, and what the user did wrong.
[src:click-cli/usability] However, effective usability tests will not generate a solution to the problems, but provide modified design guidelines for continued testing.
[src:click-cli/usability] Additionally, this style of user testing also provides an opportunity to segment feedback by demographic, attitudinal and behavioral type.
[src:click-cli/usability] The tests are carried out in the user's own environment (rather than labs) helping further simulate real-life scenario testing.
[src:click-cli/usability] This approach also provides a vehicle to easily solicit feedback from users in remote areas.
[src:click-cli/usability] There are two types, quantitative or qualitative.
[src:click-cli/usability] Quantitative use large sample sized and task based surveys.
[src:click-cli/usability] These types of studies are useful for validating suspected usability issues.
[src:click-cli/usability] Qualitative studies are best used as exploratory research, in small sample sizes but frequent, even daily iterations.
[src:click-cli/usability] The growth in mobile and associated platforms and services (e.g.: Mobile gaming has experienced 20x growth in 2010–2012) has generated a need for unmoderated remote usability testing on mobile devices, both for websites but especially for app interactions.
[src:click-cli/usability] One methodology consists of shipping cameras and special camera holding fixtures to dedicated testers, and having them record the screens of the mobile smart-phone or tablet device, usually using an HD camera.
[src:click-cli/usability] A drawback of this approach is that the finger movements of the respondent can obscure the view of the screen, in addition to the bias and logistical issues inherent in shipping special hardware to selected respondents.
[src:click-cli/usability] The Think aloud protocol is a method of gathering data that is used in both usability and psychology studies.
[src:click-cli/usability] It involves getting a user to verbalize their thought processes (i.e. expressing their opinions, thoughts, anticipations, and actions) as they perform a task or set of tasks.
[src:click-cli/usability] As a widespread method of usability testing, think aloud provides the researchers with the ability to discover what user really think during task performance and completion.
[src:click-cli/usability] Often an instructor is present to prompt the user into being more vocal as they work.
[src:click-cli/usability] Similar to the Subjects-in-Tandem method, it is useful in pinpointing problems and is relatively simple to set up.
[src:click-cli/usability] Additionally, it can provide insight into the user's attitude, which can not usually be discerned from a survey or questionnaire.
[src:click-cli/usability] Rapid Iterative Testing and Evaluation (RITE) is an iterative usability method similar to traditional "discount" usability testing.
[src:click-cli/usability] The tester and team must define a target population for testing, schedule participants to come into the lab, decide on how the users behaviors will be measured, construct a test script and have participants engage in a verbal protocol (e.g., think aloud).
[src:click-cli/usability] However it differs from these methods in that it advocates that changes to the user interface are made as soon as a problem is identified and a solution is clear.
[src:click-cli/usability] Sometimes this can occur after observing as few as 1 participant.
[src:click-cli/usability] Once the data for a participant has been collected the usability engineer and team decide if they will be making any changes to the prototype prior to the next participant.
[src:click-cli/usability] The changed interface is then tested with the remaining users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Subjects-in-tandem (also called co-discovery) is the pairing of subjects in a usability test to gather important information on the ease of use of a product.
[src:click-cli/usability] Subjects tend to discuss the tasks they have to accomplish out loud and through these discussions observers learn where the problem areas of a design are.
[src:click-cli/usability] Component-based usability testing is an approach which aims to test the usability of elementary units of an interaction system, referred to as interaction components.
[src:click-cli/usability] The approach includes component-specific quantitative measures based on user interaction recorded in log files, and component-based usability questionnaires.
[src:click-cli/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is a method of evaluating the user interaction of a working prototype or final product.
[src:click-cli/usability] It is used to evaluate the system's ease of learning.
[src:click-cli/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is useful to understand the user's thought processes and decision making when interacting with a system, specially for first-time or infrequent users.
[src:click-cli/usability] Benchmarking creates standardized test materials for a specific type of design.
[src:click-cli/usability] Four key characteristics are considered when establishing a benchmark: time to do the core task, time to fix errors, time to learn applications, and the functionality of the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Once there is a benchmark, other designs can be compared to it to determine the usability of the system.
[src:click-cli/usability] Many of the common objectives of usability studies, such as trying to understand user behavior or exploring alternative designs, must be put aside.
[src:click-cli/usability] Unlike many other usability methods or types of labs studies, benchmark studies more closely resemble true experimental psychology lab studies, with greater attention to detail on methodology, study protocol and data analysis.
[src:click-cli/usability] Meta-analysis is a statistical procedure to combine results across studies to integrate the findings.
[src:click-cli/usability] This phrase was coined in 1976 as a quantitative literature review.
[src:click-cli/usability] This type of evaluation is very powerful for determining the usability of a device because it combines multiple studies to provide very accurate quantitative support.
[src:click-cli/usability] Personas are fictitious characters created to represent a site or product's different user types and their associated demographics and technographics.
[src:click-cli/usability] Alan Cooper introduced the concept of using personas as a part of interactive design in 1998 in his book *The Inmates Are Running the Asylum*, but had used this concept since as early as 1975.
[src:click-cli/usability] Personas are a usability evaluation method that can be used at various design stages.
[src:click-cli/usability] The most typical time to create personas is at the beginning of designing so that designers have a tangible idea of who the users of their product will be.
[src:click-cli/usability] Personas are the archetypes that represent actual groups of users and their needs, which can be a general description of person, context, or usage scenario.
[src:click-cli/usability] This technique turns marketing data on target user population into a few physical concepts of users to create empathy among the design team, with the final aim of tailoring a product more closely to how the personas will use it.
[src:click-cli/usability] To gather the marketing data that personas require, several tools can be used, including online surveys, web analytics, customer feedback forms, and usability tests, and interviews with customer-service representatives.
[src:click-cli/usability] An increase in usability generally positively affects several facets of a company's output quality.
[src:click-cli/usability] By working to improve said factors, corporations can achieve their goals of increased output at lower costs, while potentially creating optimal levels of customer satisfaction.
[src:click-cli/usability] There are numerous reasons why each of these factors correlates to overall improvement.
[src:click-cli/usability] For example, making software user interfaces easier to understand reduces the need for extensive training.
[src:click-cli/usability] The improved interface tends to lower the time needed to perform tasks, and so would both raise the productivity levels for employees and reduce development time (and thus costs).
[src:click-cli/usability] Each of the aforementioned factors are not mutually exclusive; rather they should be understood to work in conjunction to form the overall workplace environment.
[src:click-cli/usability] In the 2010s, usability is recognized as an important software quality attribute, earning its place among more traditional attributes such as performance, robustness and aesthetic appearance.
[src:click-cli/usability] Various academic programs focus on usability.
[src:click-cli/usability] Several usability consultancy companies have emerged, and traditional consultancy and design firms offer similar services.
[src:click-cli/usability] There is some resistance to integrating usability work in organisations.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability is seen as a vague concept, it is difficult to measure and other areas are prioritised when IT projects run out of time or money.
[src:click-cli/usability] Usability practitioners are sometimes trained as industrial engineers, psychologists, kinesiologists, systems design engineers, or with a degree in information architecture, information or library science, or Human-Computer Interaction (HCI).
[src:click-cli/usability] More often though they are people who are trained in specific applied fields who have taken on a usability focus within their organization.
[src:click-cli/usability] Anyone who aims to make tools easier to use and more effective for their desired function within the context of work or everyday living can benefit from studying usability principles and guidelines.
[src:click-cli/usability] For those seeking to extend their training, the User Experience Professionals' Association offers online resources, reference lists, courses, conferences, and local chapter meetings.
[src:click-cli/usability] The UXPA also sponsors World Usability Day each November.
[src:click-cli/usability] Related professional organizations include the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society (HFES) and the Association for Computing Machinery's special interest groups in Computer Human Interaction (SIGCHI), Design of Communication (SIGDOC) and Computer Graphics and Interactive Techniques (SIGGRAPH).
[src:click-cli/usability] The Society for Technical Communication also has a special interest group on Usability and User Experience (UUX).
[src:click-cli/usability] They publish a quarterly newsletter called *Usability Interface*.
